<h4>Those who have participated in cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) will not be a stranger to the thought record sheet. Thought record is a tool used extensively as part of CBT.</h4>
<br><br>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-4">
    <h1>What is cognitive-behavioral therapy?<h1>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-8">
    <p>CBT is one of the most popular approaches to mental therapy today. CBT believes that we experience uncomfortable feelings such as anxiety or depression because we have been used to irrational thoughts. CBT attempts to provide the patient with alternative perspectives to look at the situation, which steers the patient towards more positive thoughts.</p>

    <p>For example, I may believe that Betty must hate me because she didn't say 'hi' to me today. As a patient, I have jumped from one fact to the other, completely forgetting other possibilities: maybe Betty had a bad hair day and is trying to stay away from people; maybe Betty was super busy today and so occupied in her thoughts that she didn't notice me and so on.</p>

    <p>By altering our thoughts to a more realistic perspective, we learn not to jump to conclusions and that the situation on-hand may not be as bad as we had thought. Once we realize that their may be a myriad of possibilites why Betty ignored us, we also start to feel better emotionally and physically.</p>

    <p>As patients gain skills in assessing stressful situations, they learn to stop and take a breath when they encounter an emotional trigger, and view the situation in a more realistic manner, thus improving their emotional well-being.</p>
  </div>
</div>
